While this situation benefits those women who are looking to divorce and have not been physically abused, the high divorce rate also comes with downsides, particularly for women who are subject to domestic violence. In order to assist women at-risk of domestic violence and to create protections for women against domestic violence and discrimination, in November 2012, the Bar Association of Moldova led an initiative to introduce and pass a resolution that the parliamentary system review three bills and approve domestic violence legislation.

The Senate as well as the House of Deputies approved the bill that among other things, mandates that criminal liability for people convicted of domestic violence take gender into account. The criminal code defines such violence as “reproducing by violence a single episode of physical or psychological abuse.” If the abuse is repeated, or if serious bodily harm has been caused, the perpetrator could face up to six years in a penal colony. In addition, lawyers will now be directly involved in all domestic violence cases by forming part of the family consultative and assistance committees and by giving legal advice. The resolution also introduces the creation of a national database for domestic violence cases to make it possible for victims of violence to systematically access statistics.
